{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"79218fa6-552a-495d-a132-5e4b05e1c94b","content":"The project path doesn't exist in this workspace, so I'll give you the configuration guidance directly.\n\n## Publishing as a `dotnet tool`\n\nAdd/ensure these properties in your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n  <RepositoryUrl>https://github.com/you/repo</RepositoryUrl>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nIf you have a `README.md`, include it:\n```xml\n<ItemGroup>\n  <None Include=\"README.md\" Pack=\"true\" PackagePath=\"/\" />\n</ItemGroup>\n```\n\n## Key points\n\n- **`PackAsTool`** — required; marks the package as a global/local tool.\n- **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users will run (e.g. `my-mcp-server`).\n- **`OutputType` must be `Exe`** — tools must be console apps.\n\n## Pack & Publish\n\n```bash\ndotnet pack -c Release\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_NUGET_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n## Users install with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server          # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's all that's needed — no special MCP-specific packaging is required since stdio tools are just regular console apps.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"22e65477-77e0-4937-a9d9-1c387c7cb361","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The path doesn't exist. The user is asking a general question about what they need to configure to publish a C# MCP server as a dotnet tool to NuGet.org. I should provide guidance rather than try to modify files.","outputTokens":565},"id":"12487323-